</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">12</emphasis>
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. languidum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="languidum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. languidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. Scale bars: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Pronotum 1.14-1.20 times as long as wide, widest at level of large lateral seta, narrowed towards base in wide, but shallow concave arc; surface as densely and coarsely punctate as on head, with indistinct, short impunctate mid-line in posterior half; scutellum with dense and pit-like punctation, interstices forming small transverse rugae.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Elytra 0.97-1.02 times as long as wide, exceedingly densely, coarsely punctate, punctures almost contiguous.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Abdominal tergites III-V with basal transverse depression, punctation of abdominal tergites IV-V moderate and sparse at base, abdominal tergite III impunctate at base; posterior halves of abdominal tergites III-V and entire surface of remaining tergites with very fine and dense punctuation.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Male.</emphasis>
Protarsomeres 1-4 moderately dilated, heart-shaped; sternite VII with patch of yellow setae on median portion and posterior margin broadly emarginate at middle; sternite VIII with posterior margin broadly emarginate at middle; aedeagus (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–18" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 13 - 18. Hesperosoma chenchangchini sp. nov. 13 - 14 habitus 15 - 17 aedeagus, lateral (15) and ventral (16) views, paramere (17) 18 female abdominal tergite X. Scale bars: 2 mm (13 - 14), 0.2 mm (15 - 18)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1075.75799.figures13-18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/620007" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">15-17</figureCitation>
) with median lobe and paramere slightly asymmetrical, paramere (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–18" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 13 - 18. Hesperosoma chenchangchini sp. nov. 13 - 14 habitus 15 - 17 aedeagus, lateral (15) and ventral (16) views, paramere (17) 18 female abdominal tergite X. Scale bars: 2 mm (13 - 14), 0.2 mm (15 - 18)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1075.75799.figures13-18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/620007" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">17</figureCitation>
) shorter than median lobe and slightly bent to left side in ventral view.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Female.</emphasis>
Tergite X (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–18" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 13 - 18. Hesperosoma chenchangchini sp. nov. 13 - 14 habitus 15 - 17 aedeagus, lateral (15) and ventral (16) views, paramere (17) 18 female abdominal tergite X. Scale bars: 2 mm (13 - 14), 0.2 mm (15 - 18)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1075.75799.figures13-18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/620007" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">18</figureCitation>
) slightly asymmetrical with posterior margin projecting at middle.
</paragraph>
